# Fluff Date: 2026-03-12 21:26:06
<overview>
<p>The Ares Assault Craft represents the combat-hardened branch of the Ares small craft lineage, tracing its origins to the primitive Mk.III of 2451 and evolving into the Mark VII, one of the most widely produced military landing craft in the Inner Sphere. Developed by IncStar Dynamics as a dedicated fighter-engagement variant, the Mk.III prioritized combat capability while retaining limited cargo capacity. Its heavier engine and upgraded armor set a template that later designers refined during the Succession Wars into the standard-technology Mark VII, produced at multiple factories and fielded by every major Inner Sphere power. The Clan adaptation, designated the Mark VII-C, brought advanced Clan technology to the same proven airframe, completing the long evolution from a primitive Age of War design into a craft that would serve in front-line roles across the entire Inner Sphere and Clan space well into the ilClan era.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Mk.III Assault Craft substantially upgrades both propulsion and protection over the base Ares design. Its more powerful primitive fusion engine nearly doubles the maximum thrust of the Mk.I, allowing the craft to pursue and intercept enemy fighters rather than simply defend. Heavier armor and additional heat sinks reflect the shift to a direct combat role.</p><p>The Mark VII carries six medium lasers across the nose, wings, and aft positions, supplemented by two nose-mounted small lasers. A Fusion 200 engine provides safe thrust 4 and maximum thrust 6. Thirteen tons of standard armor protect the hull, with nose concentration. A 31-ton cargo bay is retained alongside the weapons systems. The Mark VII's VTOL hover capability allows it to land in rough terrain without prepared strips, an advantage over conventional aerodyne designs that require prepared surfaces. The design's reliance on short-range energy weapons makes it most effective in close engagements, and it performs poorly against opponents who can maintain standoff range.</p><p>The Mark VII-C substitutes Clan medium pulse lasers for IS medium lasers and fits Clan double heat sinks, improving thermal efficiency while retaining the same combat silhouette. Clan standard armor runs one ton lighter than the IS version but provides superior protection values.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The Mark VII-C fills the same orbit-to-surface transport role in Clan service as the IS variant does in the Inner Sphere, and the two designs are operationally interchangeable for most purposes. Clan Ghost Bear operated it from their Tseng Facility in orbit around Alshain, assigning the design to transport wings supporting planetary assault operations in their occupation zone. Clan Jade Falcon added production at the Falcon's Roost Orbital Assembly Plant on Sudeten from 3074, integrating the Mark VII-C into Jade Falcon assault doctrine across the occupation zone. The upgraded pulse laser armament and double heat sink efficiency give the Mark VII-C a meaningful edge over the IS variant in close-range engagements, though for pure cargo delivery the practical differences are minimal. Both IS and Clan versions appear regularly in salvage and black market circulation across the Inner Sphere and Clan space.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>IncStar Dynamics introduced the Mk.III Assault Craft in 2451 as the third branch of the original Ares family, joining the Mk.I long-range landing craft and the Mk.II close attack landing craft on the same base hull. Where the Mk.I carried cargo and the Mk.II provided escort suppression, the Mk.III was built for direct fighter engagement. Its more powerful engine gave it the thrust to pursue and intercept, and reinforced armor allowed it to absorb damage that would have disabled the other marks. All three designs operated together in HAF landing wings through the Age of War and into the Star League period, each branch complementing the others on contested planetary approaches.</p><p>The fall of the Star League and the Succession Wars stripped away the manufacturing base that supported the original Ares family. IncStar Dynamics dissolved during the First Succession War, having already dropped the Ares name as the collapse of the Ares Conventions made the designation politically awkward. By 2824, a simplified but robust successor emerged: the Mark VII, the standard-technology heir to the Mk.I long-range landing craft branch. Produced at factories across the Successor States and the Taurian Concordat, the Mark VII carried the landing craft lineage forward while the close attack branch of the Mk.II was absorbed into broader doctrine and the assault craft branch of the Mk.III lay dormant.</p><p>The Mark VII-C emerged in 2841 with Clan technology. Clan Ghost Bear produced it at their Tseng Facility in orbit around Alshain, and Clan Jade Falcon added production at the Falcon's Roost Orbital Assembly Plant on Sudeten in 3074. Both the IS Mark VII and the Clan Mark VII-C share the introduction year of 2841 despite the decades of isolation between the two civilizations, leading historians to conclude that both designs evolved independently from a shared earlier ancestor rather than one copying the other.</p><p>The assault craft branch of the family did not stay dormant permanently. Universal Air maintained the original Ares design archives through the Succession Wars and the Clan Invasion era. After merging with Federated Boeing, the company restarted Ares attack craft production in 3066 and introduced the Mark IX in 3077, completing the revival of the third branch and reuniting all three lines of the original Ares family under active production for the first time since the Star League era.</p>
</history>

